## SERP ANALYSIS

### Competitor Summary

**Word count range:** 1,400–3,200 words (avg: ~2,100)

**Common H2 topics across top 10 ranking pages:**
1. Why almond nails dominate in 2026 / why the shape is still trending
2. Key colour directions for 2026 (neutrals vs bold split)
3. Chrome and glazed finish trends on almond
4. Minimalist / milky / quiet luxury almond nails
5. Textured and 3D almond nail trends
6. French tip almond nail trends
7. Short almond nail trends / micro almond
8. Nail art styles trending on almond (florals, aura, cat eye)
9. Seasonal breakdowns (spring/summer specific) or occasion-based
10. What nail artists and celebrities are wearing
11. Shape evolution — "modern almond" / sculptural almond
12. How to wear each trend (length, finish, application notes)

**Content approach:** Most competitors take one of two formats — either a pure gallery/listicle (design #1, design #2…) with thin context, or a general "best of 2026 nails" post where almond is one of several shapes mentioned. Almost none do a dedicated, editorially contextualised trend breakdown for almond specifically — with named trend labels, expert-backed context, seasonal relevance, and audience guidance all in one post.

**Visual patterns:** 15–30 images standard; inspiration-heavy with one image per trend/design. Video embeds rare. Pinterest-style grid layouts common. Posts with images per named trend (not just a gallery dump) have stronger engagement signals.

### Our Strategic Approach

**Differentiation:** Position this as the definitive 2026 almond nail trend edit — not a gallery, not a generic nail trends roundup. Every trend gets a named label, a clear visual descriptor, who it suits, and why it's happening now (linked to broader cultural/fashion signals). Mirellé's editorial lens (quiet luxury, elongation, refinement) gives each trend a context no basic listicle provides.

**Structure plan:** Organise around distinct named trend categories with 2–4 designs per trend rather than individual design numbers. This makes the post scannable, bookmarkable, and more defensible against thin competitor content. Add a short "what's out in 2026" section — competitors avoid this, but it addresses a real audience question and increases time-on-page.

**Tone direction:** Informed but approachable — the reader who knows what she likes but wants editorial validation before booking her next appointment.

